mmunication (Niger)|High Council for Communication]] also maintains a fund which supports private broadcasters, although its payments are criticised as political and irregular.<ref>U.S. Department of State. Report on Human Rights Practices - Niger. [http://dosfan.lib.uic.edu/ERC/democracy/hrp_index.html 1993-1995] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090616143410/http://dosfan.lib.uic.edu/ERC/democracy/hrp_index.html |date=2009-06-16 }} to [https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2006/78750.htm 2006].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Media of Niger]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.afdevinfo.com/htmlreports/ng82.html Media in Niger: the African Development Information Database].\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090304011302/http://www.gret.org/parma/uk2/ressource/edm/pdf/niger.pdf Medias Status Report:Niger]. Summary document written for the African Media Partners Network. Guy-Michel Boluvi, Les Echos du Sahel Niamey. (January 2001).\n*Addo Mahamane. [http://www.codesria.org/Links/conferences/general_assembly12/papers/addo_mahamane.pdf Enjeux et ambivalence de la libert\u00e9 de la presse dans le contexte d\u00e9mocratique africain : l\u2019exemple du Niger entre 1990 et 2008]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}. Paper presented at the [[CODESRIA]] 12th General Assembly, Yaound\u00e9, Cameroun (07-11/12/2008).\n*Marie-Soleil Frere. [https://web.archive.org/web/20101224114005/http://www.gap.ugent.be/africafocus/pdf/96-12-13-Frere.pdf NEW PRIVATE MEDIA IN FRENCH-SPEAKING WEST AFRICAN COUNTRIES : PROBLEMS AND PROSPECTS The Cases of Benin and Niger]. Afrika Focus, Vol. 12, Nr. 1-2-3, 1996, pp.&nbsp;85\u2013117\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170420152827/http://ortn.ne/ Official site]\n\n{{Niger topics}}\n{{Africa topic|Media of}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tele Sahel}}\n[[Category:Television stations in Niger]]\n[[Category:Publicly funded broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Broadcasting companies of Niger]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1964]]\n[[Category:State media]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Niger]]\n\n{{Africa-tv-stub}}\n{{Niger-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gouleg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T%C3%A9l%C3%A9_Sahel"}
{"title_page": "Ruby Mazur", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = <!-- use the image's pagename; do not include the \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and do not use brackets-->\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. -->\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = \n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Album artistry, painting\n| notable_works    = {{unbulleted list|Thousands of album covers during the 1970s, including [[Tumbling Dice]]|[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]] soundtrack cover}}\n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          =  {{URL|http://www.rubymazurgallery.com/}}\n| module           = {{Infobox person| embed = yes\n| occupation = {{unbulleted list|Former art director for Famous Music|Former art director for ABC-Dunhill|Former Paramount director of art}}\n| children         = [[Monet Mazur]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|title=A Real Gem: Pop artist Ruby Mazur leads charmed life in LV|date=2004-08-19|work=LasVegasSun.com|access-date=2018-02-19|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830045759/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|archive-date=2016-08-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''Ruby Mazur''' is an artist who was created the cover art of multiple albums for artists ranging from [[The Rolling Stones]] to [[B.B. King]] and [[Elton John]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MWVULAJHOqUC&pg=PA150&lpg=PA150&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Cocinando!: Fifty Years of Latin Album Cover Art|last=Yglesias|first=Pablo|date=2005-01-27|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568984605|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Parents\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lasvegasmercury.com/2004/MERC-Sep-30-Thu-2004/24864956.html|title=No Moss|last=Bond|first=Tiffannie|date=2004-09-30|work=[[Las Vegas Mercury]]|accessdate=2018-06-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041010225410/http://www.lasvegasmercury.com/2004/MERC-Sep-30-Thu-2004/24864956.html|archivedate=2010-10-04}}</ref> He is a former art director for [[Famous Music]] (1970),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1970-06-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref>  [[ABC-Dunhill]] (1972),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4g8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1972-11-11|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> and [[Paramount Records]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1995, he hosted an event for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', during which they called him a \"world famous artist.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1995-04-29|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=vgsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA91&lpg=PA91&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1995-05-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=5AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&dq=%22ruby+mazur%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT_Pz27fXoAhXLsJ4KHdxEAooQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=%22ruby%20mazur%22&f=false|title=Billboard|date=1995-04-29|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> Mazur created \"thousands\" of album covers during the 1970s. These covers included the 1972 [[The Rolling Stones]] album, [[Tumbling Dice]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2014/03/22/artist-who-created-tounge-logo-calls-jagger-very-bad-guy.html|title=Artist who created tongue logo calls Jagger \"a very bad guy\"|date=2014-03-22|work=Fox News|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816150644/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2014/03/22/artist-who-created-tounge-logo-calls-jagger-very-bad-guy.html|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA108&lpg=PA108&dq=ruby+mazur+tumbling+dice#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1995-04-08|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> and ones for [[B.B. King]], [[Jimmy Buffett]], [[Dave Mason]], [[Dusty Springfield]], and [[Elton John]]. Mazur also created the cover for the soundtrack to the 1971 film, \"[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory|Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory]]\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|title=A Real Gem: Pop artist Ruby Mazur leads charmed life in LV|date=2004-08-19|work=LasVegasSun.com|access-date=2017-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830045759/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|archive-date=2016-08-30|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn a 2004 interview with the ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', Mazur cited the increasingly \"formula[ic]\" creation of album covers which started during the late 1980s as the reason that he started painting.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the mid 1990s, he created a painting of a model with a cigar in her hand {{Em dash}} a suggested addition by a friend {{Em dash}} that was purchased by Saudi Arabian Prince Mohammed Al-sudairy before the ink even dried.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Feud with Jagger ==\nSince the 1980s, Mazur has been in a feud with [[Mick Jagger]] after Jagger allegedly refused to give him trademark rights to the [[Tumbling Dice]] cover, which he created.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2014/03/22/artist-rips-jagger-mick-a-bad-guy-who-drove-me-to-brink-of-suicide/|title=Artist rips Jagger: Mick a \u2018bad guy\u2019 who drove me to brink of suicide|last=Smith|first=Stephanie|date=2014-03-22|website=Page Six|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In the 1990s, Mazur attempted to sue Jagger for trademark infringement, but the [[statute of limitations]] had passed. It is estimated he could have earned in excess of $100 million from the logo.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mazur, Ruby}}\n[[Category:Paramount Records]]\n[[Category:American art directors]]\n[[Category:Album-cover and concert-poster artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = <!-- use the image's pagename; do not include the \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and do not use brackets-->\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. -->\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = \n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Album artistry, painting\n| notable_works    = {{unbulleted list|Thousands of album covers during the 1970s, including [[Tumbling Dice]]|[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]] soundtrack cover}}\n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          =  {{URL|http://www.rubymazurgallery.com/}}\n| module           = {{Infobox person| embed = yes\n| occupation = {{unbulleted list|Former art director for Famous Music|Former art director for ABC-Dunhill|Former Paramount director of art}}\n| children         = [[Monet Mazur]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|title=A Real Gem: Pop artist Ruby Mazur leads charmed life in LV|date=2004-08-19|work=LasVegasSun.com|access-date=2018-02-19|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830045759/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|archive-date=2016-08-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''Ruby Mazur''' is an artist who was created the cover art of multiple albums for artists ranging from [[The Rolling Stones]] to [[B.B. King]] and [[Elton John]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MWVULAJHOqUC&pg=PA150&lpg=PA150&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Cocinando!: Fifty Years of Latin Album Cover Art|last=Yglesias|first=Pablo|date=2005-01-27|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568984605|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Parents\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lasvegasmercury.com/2004/MERC-Sep-30-Thu-2004/24864956.html|title=No Moss|last=Bond|first=Tiffannie|date=2004-09-30|work=[[Las Vegas Mercury]]|accessdate=2018-06-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041010225410/http://www.lasvegasmercury.com/2004/MERC-Sep-30-Thu-2004/24864956.html|archivedate=2010-10-04}}</ref> He is a former art director for [[Famous Music]] (1970),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1970-06-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref>  [[ABC-Dunhill]] (1972),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4g8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1972-11-11|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> and [[Paramount Records]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1995, he hosted an event for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', during which they called him a \"world famous artist.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1995-04-29|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=vgsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA91&lpg=PA91&dq=%22Ruby+Mazur%22#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1995-05-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=5AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&dq=%22ruby+mazur%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT_Pz27fXoAhXLsJ4KHdxEAooQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=%22ruby%20mazur%22&f=false|title=Billboard|date=1995-04-29|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> Mazur created \"thousands\" of album covers during the 1970s. These covers included the 1972 [[The Rolling Stones]] album, [[Tumbling Dice]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2014/03/22/artist-who-created-tounge-logo-calls-jagger-very-bad-guy.html|title=Artist who created tongue logo calls Jagger \"a very bad guy\"|date=2014-03-22|work=Fox News|access-date=2017-08-16|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816150644/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2014/03/22/artist-who-created-tounge-logo-calls-jagger-very-bad-guy.html|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA108&lpg=PA108&dq=ruby+mazur+tumbling+dice#v=onepage|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1995-04-08|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> and ones for [[B.B. King]], [[Jimmy Buffett]], [[Dave Mason]], [[Dusty Springfield]], and [[Elton John]]. Mazur also created the cover for the soundtrack to the 1971 film, \"[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory|Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory]]\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|title=A Real Gem: Pop artist Ruby Mazur leads charmed life in LV|date=2004-08-19|work=LasVegasSun.com|access-date=2017-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830045759/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/aug/19/a-real-gem-pop-artist-ruby-mazur-leads-charmed-lif/|archive-date=2016-08-30|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn a 2004 interview with the ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', Mazur cited the increasingly \"formula[ic]\" creation of album covers which started during the late 1980s as the reason that he started painting.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the mid 1990s, he created a painting of a model with a cigar in her hand {{Em dash}} a suggested addition by a friend {{Em dash}} that was purchased by Saudi Arabian Prince Mohammed Al-sudairy before the ink even dried.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Feud with Jagger ==\nSince the 1980s, Mazur has been in a feud with [[Mick Jagger]] after Jagger allegedly refused to give him trademark rights to the [[Tumbling Dice]] cover, which he created.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2014/03/22/artist-rips-jagger-mick-a-bad-guy-who-drove-me-to-brink-of-suicide/|title=Artist rips Jagger: Mick a \u2018bad guy\u2019 who drove me to brink of suicide|last=Smith|first=Stephanie|date=2014-03-22|website=Page Six|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In the 1990s, Mazur attempted to sue Jagger for trademark infringement, but the [[statute of limitations]] had passed. It is estimated he could have earned in excess of $100 million from the logo.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Paramount Records]]\n[[Category:American art directors]]\n[[Category:Album-cover and concert-poster artists]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_Mazur"}
{"title_page": "Henry Hart (author)", "text_new": "'''Henry Hart''' (born 1954) is the Hickman Professor of [[Humanities]] at the [[College of William and Mary]]<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold |title=Seamus Heaney |year=2002|isbn=0-7910-6816-1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=C1_JzE_JWFUC&pg=PA66&dq=Henry+Hart+poet#v=onepage&q=Henry%20Hart%20poet&f=false}}</ref> in [[Williamsburg, Virginia]]. In addition to three books of poetry (''The Ghost Ship'' (1990),  ''The Rooster Mask'' (1998),  and ''Background Radiation'' (2007)) he has written critical works on such poets as [[Seamus Heaney]], [[Geoffrey Hill]], and [[Robert Lowell]]. He edited ''The [[James Dickey]] Reader'' (1999) and his biography ''James Dickey: The World as a Lie'' (2000), was a finalist in nonfiction for the [[Southern Book Critics Circle Award]].  He also edited ''The Wadsworth Themes in American Literature Series'' (2009). (2009) His poems and essays have appeared in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry]]'', ''[[Kenyon Review]]'', ''[[Southern Review]]'', ''[[Sewanee Review]]'', ''[[Denver Quarterly]]'', and numerous other journals. Hart was a founding editor of ''Verse'', an international poetry journal.  In 2010 he won the Carole Weinstein Prize for Poetry. On July 2, 2018, he was sworn in as the 17th [[Poet Laureate of Virginia]] in the commonwealth's capital of Richmond.<ref name=\"Ducibella\">{{cite news |last1=Ducibella |first1=Jim |title=Henry Hart has a new title: poet laureate of Virginia |url=https://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2018/henry-hart-has-a-new-title-poet-laureate-of-virginia.php |accessdate=17 September 2018 |work=William & Mary News & Media |date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zdn2 James Dickey: The World as a Lie research files, 1990-2005]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hart, Henry}}\n[[Category:Poets Laureate of Virginia]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary faculty]]\n[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n\n\n{{Editor-stub}}\n{{US-English-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Henry Hart''' (born 1954) is the Hickman Professor of [[Humanities]] at the [[College of William and Mary]]<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold |title=Seamus Heaney |year=2002|isbn=0-7910-6816-1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=C1_JzE_JWFUC&pg=PA66&dq=Henry+Hart+poet#v=onepage&q=Henry%20Hart%20poet&f=false}}</ref> in [[Williamsburg, Virginia]]. In addition to three books of poetry (''The Ghost Ship'' (1990),  ''The Rooster Mask'' (1998),  and ''Background Radiation'' (2007)) he has written critical works on such poets as [[Seamus Heaney]], [[Geoffrey Hill]], and [[Robert Lowell]]. He edited ''The [[James Dickey]] Reader'' (1999) and his biography ''James Dickey: The World as a Lie'' (2000), was a finalist in nonfiction for the [[Southern Book Critics Circle Award]].  He also edited ''The Wadsworth Themes in American Literature Series'' (2009). (2009) His poems and essays have appeared in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry]]'', ''[[Kenyon Review]]'', ''[[Southern Review]]'', ''[[Sewanee Review]]'', ''[[Denver Quarterly]]'', and numerous other journals. Hart was a founding editor of ''Verse'', an international poetry journal.  In 2010 he won the Carole Weinstein Prize for Poetry. On July 2, 2018, he was sworn in as the 17th [[Poet Laureate of Virginia]] in the commonwealth's capital of Richmond.<ref name=\"Ducibella\">{{cite news |last1=Ducibella |first1=Jim |title=Henry Hart has a new title: poet laureate of Virginia |url=https://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2018/henry-hart-has-a-new-title-poet-laureate-of-virginia.php |accessdate=17 September 2018 |work=William & Mary News & Media |date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hart, Henry}}\n[[Category:Poets Laureate of Virginia]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary faculty]]\n[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n\n\n{{Editor-stub}}\n{{US-English-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "A.C.Butner", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Hart_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Venirauto Turpial", "text_new": "The '''Venirauto Turpial''' is a four-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] produced in [[Venezuela]] by [[Venirauto]], a joint Venezuelan-[[Iran]]ian venture.<ref>Romero, Simon. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/13/world/americas/13venez.html ''Caracas Journal: Detroit\u2019s Monsters Thrive on a Diet of Cheap Gas'']\", ''[[New York Times]]'', December 12, 2010.</ref>  It is named for the national bird of Venezuela.  The production plant is located in [[Maracay]] west of [[Caracas]] and has been producing vehicles since at least July, 2007.<ref name=\"vanalysis\">Carlson, Chris: \"[http://venezuelanalysis.com/news/2491 ''Venezuelan-Iranian Car Company Releases First Models'']\", venezuelanalysis.com Retrieved December 17, 2010.</ref>  The vehicle is based on the [[Kia Pride]] and was originally priced at [[Venezuelan bol\u00edvar|Bs.]] 17 million (US$7,906).<ref name=\"vanalysis\"/> According to the German newspapers [[die Tageszeitung]] the plant nearly produces no cars.<ref>Zelik, Raul: \"[http://taz.de/1/politik/amerika/artikel/1/zwoelf-jahre-chavismus-in-venezuela/ ''Zw\u00f6lf Jahre Chavismus in Venezuela'']\", taz.de Retrieved May 23, 2011.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140223001213/http://www.venirauto.com.ve/ Website of manufacturer Venirauto] {{in lang|es}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Cars of Venezuela]]\n\n\n{{automobile-stub}}\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2007]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Venirauto Turpial''' is a four-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] produced in [[Venezuela]] by [[Venirauto]], a joint Venezuelan-[[Iran]]ian venture.<ref>Romero, Simon. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/13/world/americas/13venez.html ''Caracas Journal: Detroit\u2019s Monsters Thrive on a Diet of Cheap Gas'']\", ''[[New York Times]]'', December 12, 2010.</ref>  It is named for the national bird of Venezuela.  The production plant is located in [[Maracay]] west of [[Caracas]] 